g.text: Offered Evacuation Assistance

g.text: Attended Zelenskyy's Inauguration

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Rinat Akhmetov
g.text: Accused of Backing Coup Plot

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Rishi Sunak
g.text: Met During NATO Summit

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Ruslan Stefanchuk
g.text: Chairman of Verkhovna Rada During EU Membership Application

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Salome Zourabichvili
g.text: Attended Zelenskyy's Inauguration

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Sean Penn
g.text: Interviewed for Documentary

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Serhiy Shefir
g.text: Close Aide and Alleged Financial Arrangements

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Tim Cook
g.text: Met During U.S. Visit

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Vadym Prystaiko
g.text: Appointed Foreign Minister

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Viktor Medvedchuk
g.text: Alleged Meeting in Oman

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Viktor Yanukovych
g.text: Alleged Offer of Political Control

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Volodymyr Groysman
g.text: Prime Minister During Zelenskyy's Presidency

g.title: Xi Jinping
g.text: Xi Jinping
• He became the General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party on November 15, 2012, and the President of China on March 14, 2013.
• He launched an anti-corruption campaign targeting high-ranking officials and ordinary party functionaries.

g.title: Volodymyr Zelenskyy->Xi Jinping
g.text: Refused to Speak with Zelenskyy

g.title: Vovan and Lexus
g.text: Vovan and Lexus
• They began collaborating in 2014, targeting critics of the Russian government.
• Their pranks often involve impersonating political figures, including calls to U.S. and European leaders.

g.title: Vovan and Lexus->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Impersonated in prank call to Christine Lagarde

g.title: Vsevolod Chentsov
g.text: Vsevolod Chentsov
• Appointed head of the Mission of Ukraine to the European Union on 25 August 2021.
• Served as Ukraine's ambassador to the Netherlands from 2017 to 2021.

g.title: Vsevolod Chentsov->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Served as Head of Mission under President Volodymyr Zelenskyy

g.title: Vsevolod Kniaziev
g.text: Vsevolod Kniaziev
• Detained on 15 May 2023 for allegedly receiving a $2.7 million bribe.
• Served as President of the Supreme Court of Ukraine from 1 December 2021 to 16 May 2023.

g.title: Vsevolod Kniaziev->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Served under as President of Ukraine during tenure as President of the Supreme Court

g.title: Wendy Rogers (politician)
g.text: Wendy Rogers (politician)
• Faced censure by the Arizona Senate in March 2022 for controversial remarks.
• Served in the U.S. Air Force from 1976 to 1996, retiring as a Lieutenant Colonel.

g.title: Wendy Rogers (politician)->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Criticized with antisemitic conspiracy theories about

g.title: Wojciech Sawicki
g.text: Wojciech Sawicki
• Served as Secretary General of the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe from 2011 to 2021.
• Held the position of Secretary General of the Polish Senate from 1990 to 1996.

g.title: Wojciech Sawicki->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Recipient of the Order of Prince Yaroslav the Wise awarded by Volodymyr Zelenskyy

g.title: Yaakov Bleich
g.text: Yaakov Bleich
• Served as Chief Rabbi of the Podil synagogue in Kyiv since 1990.
• Born on October 19, 1964, in Brooklyn, New York, USA.

g.title: Yaakov Bleich->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Received a request for prayers for Ukraine during the 2022 conflict

g.title: Yaroslav Hunka scandal
g.text: Yaroslav Hunka scandal
• Volunteered in 1943 to join the SS Division Galicia, a unit of the Waffen-SS, during World War II.
• In 2023, he was controversially recognized in the Canadian Parliament, leading to a political scandal.

g.title: Yaroslav Hunka scandal->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Ukrainian President present during the scandalous event

g.title: Yaroslav Kendzior
g.text: Yaroslav Kendzior
• Served as People's Deputy of Ukraine from 1990 to 1998 and from 1999 to 2012.
• Removed from People's Movement of Ukraine in 2009 due to political disagreements.

g.title: Yaroslav Kendzior->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Critic in the 2019 Ukrainian presidential election

g.title: Yaroslav Lahuta
g.text: Yaroslav Lahuta
• Served as acting Governor of Zhytomyr Oblast from 24 June 2019 to 8 August 2019.
• Appointed as head of the Darnytsia District State Administration in Kyiv on 18 May 2020.

g.title: Yaroslav Lahuta->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed by Volodymyr Zelenskyy as chairman of the Darnytsia District State Administration

g.title: Yaroslav Yanushevych
g.text: Yaroslav Yanushevych
• Served as Governor of Kherson Oblast from 3 August 2022 to 24 January 2023.
• His term as governor was disputed due to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.

g.title: Yaroslav Yanushevych->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed by

g.title: Yaryna Chornohuz
g.text: Yaryna Chornohuz
• Joined the Ukrainian military in 2019 as a medic with the Hospitallers Medical Battalion.
• Became a contract soldier for the Ukrainian Armed Forces after her partner was killed in action in 2020.

g.title: Yaryna Chornohuz->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Protester against Zelenskyy's 2020 peace council decision

g.title: Yevgeny Prigozhin
g.text: Yevgeny Prigozhin
• Died in a plane crash in Tver Oblast, Russia, on August 23, 2023, under circumstances suggesting possible sabotage.
• He led the Wagner Group, a private military company, from its establishment on February 22, 2014, until his death on August 23, 2023.

g.title: Yevgeny Prigozhin->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Opposed during Russian invasion of Ukraine

g.title: Yevhen Koshovyi
g.text: Yevhen Koshovyi
• Host of the TV program 'League of Laughter' since 2019.
• Born on April 7, 1983, in Kivsharivka, Soviet Union (now Ukraine).

g.title: Yevhen Koshovyi->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Close Friend and Successor as Host of 'League of Laughter'

g.title: Yevhen Marchuk
g.text: Yevhen Marchuk
• Served as the 4th Prime Minister of Ukraine from March 1995 to May 1996.
• Was the first Chief of the Security Service of Ukraine from November 1991 to July 1994.

g.title: Yevhen Marchuk->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: President during Marchuk's representation in the Trilateral Contact Group

g.title: Yevhen Moisiuk
g.text: Yevhen Moisiuk
• Commanded the defense of Donetsk Airport during the Russo-Ukrainian War.
• Served as Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces of Ukraine since 29 July 2021.

g.title: Yevhen Moisiuk->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Deputy Commander-in-Chief under President Volodymyr Zelenskyy

g.title: Yevhen Murayev
g.text: Yevhen Murayev
• Served as People's Deputy of Ukraine from 2012 to 2019.
• Founded and led the political party Nashi, which was banned in June 2022.

g.title: Yevhen Murayev->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Assets blocked by Zelenskyy's decree in 2025

g.title: Yevheniy Shevchenko (politician)
g.text: Yevheniy Shevchenko (politician)
• Expelled from the Servant of the People party in May 2021 after meeting with Belarusian leader Alexander Lukashenko.
• Elected as People's Deputy of Ukraine from Zaporizhzhia Oblast's 76th electoral district on 29 August 2019.

g.title: Yevheniy Shevchenko (politician)->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Representative of Zelenskyy's 2019 presidential campaign

g.title: Yulia Laputina
g.text: Yulia Laputina
• Served as Minister of Veterans Affairs of Ukraine since December 2020 under President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.
• Promoted to the rank of major general in the Security Service of Ukraine in March 2020.

g.title: Yulia Laputina->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Minister for Veterans Affairs appointed during Volodymyr Zelenskyy's presidency

g.title: Yulia Mykytenko
g.text: Yulia Mykytenko
• Participated in the Battle of Svitlodarsk and awarded the Order of Bohdan Khmelnytsky and Order for Courage.
• Served in the Ukrainian Ground Forces from 2016-2021 and rejoined in 2022.

g.title: Yulia Mykytenko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Protested against policies of

g.title: Yulia Paliychuk
g.text: Yulia Paliychuk
• Became the spokeswoman of the Servant of the People in the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine in September 2019.
• Was a candidate for People's Deputies of Ukraine in July 2019, listed as number 150 for the Servant of the People party.

g.title: Yulia Paliychuk->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Spokeswoman for the political party led by Volodymyr Zelenskyy

g.title: Yulia Svyrydenko
g.text: Yulia Svyrydenko
• Appointed as First Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Economic Development and Trade of Ukraine on 4 November 2021.
• Served as Deputy Head of the Office of the President of Ukraine from 22 December 2020 to 4 November 2021.

g.title: Yulia Svyrydenko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed by President Volodymyr Zelenskyy as First Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Economic Development and Trade

g.title: Yulia Tolopa
g.text: Yulia Tolopa
• Joined the Ukrainian Aidar Battalion in 2014 to fight in the Russo-Ukrainian War.
• Faced threats from the Russian government and media, and struggled to obtain Ukrainian nationality, which she finally received in 2021.

g.title: Yulia Tolopa->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Granted Ukrainian nationality by

g.title: Yulia Tymoshenko
g.text: Yulia Tymoshenko
• Served as Prime Minister of Ukraine from 24 January to 8 September 2005 and again from 18 December 2007 to 4 March 2010.
• Co-led the Orange Revolution and was a key figure in Ukraine's 2004 political transformation.

g.title: Yulia Tymoshenko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Political Rival in 2019 Presidential Election

g.title: Yuliia Paievska
g.text: Yuliia Paievska
• Founded the volunteer ambulance corps 'Taira's Angels' during the Russo-Ukrainian War.
• Captured by Russian soldiers on March 16, 2022, and released on June 17, 2022.

g.title: Yuliia Paievska->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Ukrainian President who announced her release

g.title: Yuliya Didenko
g.text: Yuliya Didenko
• Elected as a People's Deputy of Ukraine in 2019, representing the Servant of the People party.
• Serves on the Verkhovna Rada's Committee on Finance, Tax and Customs Policy.

g.title: Yuliya Didenko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Elected as People's Deputy under his Servant of the People party

g.title: Yuliya Sokolovska
g.text: Yuliya Sokolovska
• Appointed Minister of Social Policy of Ukraine on 29 August 2019.
• Served as Deputy Head of the Office of the President of Ukraine responsible for social affairs starting 12 March 2020.

g.title: Yuliya Sokolovska->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed by as Deputy Head of the Office of the President of Ukraine

g.title: Yuri Bashmet
g.text: Yuri Bashmet
• Born on 24 January 1953 in Rostov-on-Don, Russian SFSR, Soviet Union.
• Graduated from the Moscow Conservatory in 1976, where he studied under Vadim Borisovsky and Fyodor Druzhinin.

g.title: Yuri Bashmet->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Stripped Bashmet of the Order of Merit (Ukraine)

g.title: Yurii Hudymenko
g.text: Yurii Hudymenko
• Served as a military engineer unit commander during the Russo-Ukrainian War, participating in key battles.
• Leader of the 'Demokratychna Sokyra' movement and co-founder of the party in 2018.

g.title: Yurii Hudymenko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Recipient of Order for Courage under his presidency

g.title: Yurii Sodol
g.text: Yurii Sodol
• Appointed Commander of the Joint Forces of the Armed Forces of Ukraine in February 2024, serving until June 2024.
• Served as Commander of the Ukrainian Marine Corps from March 2018 to February 2024.

g.title: Yurii Sodol->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed and dismissed by as Commander of the Joint Forces

g.title: Yuriy Boyko
g.text: Yuriy Boyko
• Served as Vice Prime Minister of Ukraine from 24 December 2012 to 27 February 2014.
• Held the position of Minister of Energy from 2006 to 2007 and again from 2010 to 2012.

g.title: Yuriy Boyko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Stripped Boyko of state awards in 2025

g.title: Yuriy Lebid
g.text: Yuriy Lebid
• Appointed Acting Head of the Eastern Territorial Department of the National Guard of Ukraine in spring 2014 and was kidnapped in Donetsk on 12 May 2014, released a week later.
• Appointed Commander of the National Guard of Ukraine on 25 February 2022.

g.title: Yuriy Lebid->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed by as Commander of the National Guard of Ukraine

g.title: Yuriy Lutsenko
g.text: Yuriy Lutsenko
• Served as the Prosecutor General of Ukraine from 12 May 2016 to 29 August 2019.
• Involved in the Trump–Ukraine scandal, where he was accused of working with Rudy Giuliani to find information on Joe Biden.

g.title: Yuriy Lutsenko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Dismissed him as Prosecutor General

g.title: Yuriy Malashko
g.text: Yuriy Malashko
• Served as Governor of Zaporizhzhia Oblast from February 7, 2023, to February 2, 2024.
• Appointed by President Volodymyr Zelenskyy during the Russian invasion of Ukraine.

g.title: Yuriy Malashko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed by

g.title: Yuriy Polyukhovych
g.text: Yuriy Polyukhovych
• Appointed as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of Ukraine to Peru on 23 December 2022.
• Served as Acting Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine starting 10 March 2020.

g.title: Yuriy Polyukhovych->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed by as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary

g.title: Yuriy Prylypko
g.text: Yuriy Prylypko
• Killed by Russian soldiers on 7 March 2022 during the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
• Served as mayor of Hostomel from 25 October 2015 until 7 March 2022.

g.title: Yuriy Prylypko->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Mayor of Hostomel during Zelenskyy's presidency

g.title: Yuriy Rybchynskyi
g.text: Yuriy Rybchynskyi
• Recipient of the Hero of Ukraine award on 22 August 2020.
• Born on 22 May 1945 in Podil, Ukrainian SSR, Soviet Union (now Ukraine).

g.title: Yuriy Rybchynskyi->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Awarded Hero of Ukraine by

g.title: Yuriy Zdebskyi
g.text: Yuriy Zdebskyi
• Elected as People's Deputy of Ukraine for Kharkiv Oblast's 172nd electoral district on 29 August 2019.
• Served in the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine from 1990 to 2018, retiring as a colonel.

g.title: Yuriy Zdebskyi->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Campaign Worker for 2019 Presidential Election

g.title: Zoran Milanović
g.text: Zoran Milanović
• Served as Prime Minister of Croatia from 23 December 2011 to 22 January 2016.
• Elected as President of Croatia, taking office on 19 February 2020.

g.title: Zoran Milanović->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Criticized during Russian invasion of Ukraine

g.title: Zoriana Skaletska
g.text: Zoriana Skaletska
• Appointed as the Minister of Healthcare of Ukraine on 29 August 2019, serving until 4 March 2020.
• Graduated from the National University of Kyiv-Mohyla Academy in 2002 and studied at Maria Curie-Skłodowska University until 2006.

g.title: Zoriana Skaletska->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Appointed by Volodymyr Zelenskyy as Minister of Healthcare of Ukraine

g.title: Zuzana Čaputová
g.text: Zuzana Čaputová
• Served as the fifth President of Slovakia from 2019 to 2024, being the first woman and youngest person to hold the office.
• Gained prominence by leading a successful campaign against a toxic landfill in Pezinok, earning the Goldman Environmental Prize in 2016.

g.title: Zuzana Čaputová->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Collaborated with as President of Ukraine

g.title: Étienne de Poncins
g.text: Étienne de Poncins
• Appointed as French Ambassador to Ukraine in August 2019.
• Relocated to Lviv during the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine and reopened the French embassy in Kyiv on 15 April 2022.

g.title: Étienne de Poncins->Volodymyr Zelenskyy
g.text: Met with Volodymyr Zelenskyy as French Ambassador to Ukraine
